rotect and regenerate endangered species from the Great Barrier Reef to the Arctic and the Amazon. We discover the shocking impacts of noise pollution on both animals and plants. We learn how artificial intelligence can decode nonhuman sounds, and meet the researchers building dictionaries in East African Elephant and Sperm Whalish. At the frontiers of innovation, we explore digitally mediated dialogues with bats and honeybees. Technology often distracts us from nature, but what if it could reconnect us instead?The Sounds of Life offers hope for environmental conservation and affirms humanity’s relationship with nature in the digital age. After learning about the unsuspected wonders of nature’s sounds, we will never see walks outdoors in the same way again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBioacousticsxResearch. 0aLandscape ecology. 0aNatural historyxTechnique. 0aNature soundsxRecording and reproducing. 0aNoise pollution. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingxDigital techniques. 7aNATURE / Animals.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAnalogy.  aAnimal echolocation.  aArtificial reef.  aBeehive fence.  aBioacoustics.  aBiodiversity.  aBiologist.  aBird.  aBowhead whale.  aCharismatic megafauna.  aConsciousness.  aContemporary society.  aCoral reef.  aCrustacean.  aEcology.  aEcosystem.  aEnvironmental noise.  aEthology.  aField recording.  aFinding.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aHatchling.  aHearing range.  aHoney bee.  aHuman intelligence.  aHuman.  aHydrophone.  aInsect.  aLanguage.  aLarva.  aLifeway.  aListening.  aLongevity.  aLoudness.  aLouse.  aMammal.  aMarine biology.  aMarine mammal.  aMicrobat.  aMicrophone.  aNoise pollution.  aNutrient.  aOdor.  aOrganism.  aPheromone.  aPhysiology.  aPlant.  aPositive feedback